Dataset Information:

This data set includes descriptions of hypothetical samples corresponding to 23 species of gilled mushrooms in the Agaricus and Lepiota Family (pp. 500-525). Each species is identified as definitely edible, definitely poisonous, or of unknown edibility and not recommended. This latter class was combined with the poisonous one. The Guide clearly states that there is no simple rule for determining the edibility of a mushroom; no rule like 'leaflets three, let it be' for Poisonous Oak and Ivy.

  1. class: edible=e,poisonous=p
  2. cap-shape: bell=b,conical=c,convex=x,flat=f,knobbed=k,sunken=s
  3. cap-surface: fibrous=f,grooves=g,scaly=y,smooth=s
  4. cap-color: brown=n,buff=b,cinnamon=c,gray=g,green=r,pink=p,purple=u,red=e,white=w,yellow=y
  5. bruises?: bruises=t,no=f
  6. odor: almond=a,anise=l,creosote=c,fishy=y,foul=f,musty=m,none=n,pungent=p,spicy=s
  7. gill-attachment: attached=a,descending=d,free=f,notched=n
  8. gill-spacing: close=c,crowded=w,distant=d
  9. gill-size: broad=b,narrow=n
  10. gill-color: black=k,brown=n,buff=b,chocolate=h,gray=g,green=r,orange=o,pink=p,purple=u,red=e,white=w,yellow=y
  11. stalk-shape: enlarging=e,tapering=t
  12. stalk-root: bulbous=b,club=c,cup=u,equal=e,rhizomorphs=z,rooted=r,missing=?
  13. stalk-surface-above-ring: fibrous=f,scaly=y,silky=k,smooth=s
  14. stalk-surface-below-ring: fibrous=f,scaly=y,silky=k,smooth=s
  15. stalk-color-above-ring: brown=n,buff=b,cinnamon=c,gray=g,orange=o,pink=p,red=e,white=w,yellow=y
  16. stalk-color-below-ring: brown=n,buff=b,cinnamon=c,gray=g,orange=o,pink=p,red=e,white=w,yellow=y
  17. veil-type: partial=p,universal=u
  18. veil-color: brown=n,orange=o,white=w,yellow=y
  19. ring-number: none=n,one=o,two=t
  20. ring-type: cobwebby=c,evanescent=e,flaring=f,large=l,none=n,pendant=p,sheathing=s,zone=z
  21. spore-print-color: black=k,brown=n,buff=b,chocolate=h,green=r, orange=o,purple=u,white=w,yellow=y
  22. population: abundant=a,clustered=c,numerous=n,scattered=s,several=v,solitary=y
  23. habitat: grasses=g,leaves=l,meadows=m,paths=p,urban=u,waste=w,woods=d

Introduction

In this tutorial, I will demonstrate advanced Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) techniques:

  • Create multi-plot data visualizations for feature analysis
  • Custom heatmap correlation analysis
  • Using a Random Forest model for preliminary predictive analysis

Rules for Edible Mushrooms

This project involves a classic machine learning dataset that I will use to demonstrate some advanced Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) techniques in order to answer a hypothesis about the potential for 'rules' for determining whether an unknown wild mushroom is poisonous or edible. I think it will be interesting to demonstrate on this project that machine learning can be used effectively for EDA - thereby breaking the pattern of ML only being used for classification tasks.

Null Hypothesis

In following with the spirit of this dataset, I am formulating a null hypothesis which I will attempt to disprove through my analysis. When considering the problem of finding a wild mushroom and trying to determine whether it is poisonous or not, there are only two types of 'simple rule' that are analogous to the previously mentioned rule about poisonous leaves having three pointy leaflets. I am characterizing a 'simple rule' as a single feature discriminator

Types of a possible 'simple rule' for poisonous/edible:

  1. If [feature], then the mushroom is edible
  2. If [feature], then the mushroom is poisonous

Ideally, the 'simple rule' would be 100% efficacious, especially since a wrong classification could kill the mushroom eater

Thinking logically, if there was a feature that provided a 100% edible rule (meaning 100% NOT poisonous), that would be much more useful than a feature that provided a 100% poisonous rule. If a mushroom doesn't match a 100% poisonous rule, this doesn't mean that it is safe to eat, because it could just be a different type of poisonous mushroom

What this analysis is looking for is a 'simple rule' that provides a 100% NOT poisonous prediction

Therefore the null hypothesis is that there is no 'simple rule' that exists to provide a 100% NOT poisonous prediction

About the Dataset

This dataset was curated and donated to the UCI Machine Learning Repository on April 27, 1984 (38 years ago - in 2022). The reason why the dataset was curated is because researchers wanted to know if there was a 'simple rule' for determining the edibility of a wild mushroom. They make an analogy to a 'simple rule' for figuring out if a leaf is poisonous - such as Poisonous Oak or Ivy

Data Processing

I chose this dataset because it is already pretty clean - as I didn't want the tutorial to be about data cleaning. I did have to make some simple edits, and I made one major change in recoding the data values as whole words (EXAMPLE: 'b' --> 'brown') because it will make the data visualization code more clean and readable. At the end of this cell, I also split the dataset on the target variable so that I can prepare for my data visualization concept (stacked bar charts)

In [71]:
# replace question mark with NULL for clarity
df_mushroom.replace('?', 'NULL', inplace=True)

# convert categorical labels to full words
df_mushroom_long = pd.concat([df_mushroom['class'].map(target_dict),
                              df_mushroom['cap-shape'].map(cap_shape_dict),
                              df_mushroom['cap-surface'].map(cap_surface_dict),
                              df_mushroom['cap-color'].map(cap_color_dict),
                              df_mushroom['bruises?'].map(bruises_dict),
                              df_mushroom['odor'].map(odor_dict),
                              df_mushroom['gill-attachment'].map(gill_attachment_dict),
                              df_mushroom['gill-spacing'].map(gill_spacing_dict),
                              df_mushroom['gill-size'].map(gill_size_dict),
                              df_mushroom['gill-color'].map(gill_color_dict),
                              df_mushroom['stalk-shape'].map(stalk_shape_dict),
                              df_mushroom['stalk-root'].map(stalk_root_dict),
                              df_mushroom['stalk-surface-above-ring'].map(stalk_surface_dict),
                              df_mushroom['stalk-surface-below-ring'].map(stalk_surface_dict),
                              df_mushroom['stalk-color-above-ring'].map(stalk_color_dict),
                              df_mushroom['stalk-color-below-ring'].map(stalk_color_dict),
                              df_mushroom['veil-type'].map(veil_type_dict),
                              df_mushroom['veil-color'].map(veil_color_dict),
                              df_mushroom['ring-number'].map(ring_number_dict),
                              df_mushroom['ring-type'].map(ring_type_dict),
                              df_mushroom['spore-print-color'].map(spore_print_color_dict),
                              df_mushroom['population'].map(population_dict),
                              df_mushroom['habitat'].map(habitat_dict)], axis=1)

# split dataframe based on target variable (poisonous/edible)
df_mushroom_poisonous = df_mushroom_long[df_mushroom_long['class'] == 'poisonous']
df_mushroom_edible = df_mushroom_long[df_mushroom_long['class'] == 'edible']

# reindex split dataframes
df_mushroom_poisonous.index =  range(len(df_mushroom_poisonous))
df_mushroom_edible.index = range(len(df_mushroom_edible))

Custom Multi-Plot Bar Charts for Feature Analysis

As my data is all categorical variables (no numeric variables), I am not doing any descriptive statistics. What I wanted was the value counts on each of the features, but I ended up working that into my data visualization concept

I know that I can't fit all the bar plots on one figure, so I decided to segment them into logical groups (and I put the leftover features in 'Other'). What I ended up with here was three figures with four bar plots each and one figure with six bar plots. I used horizontal bars so that the labels would be easy to read. I coded poisonous as red and edible as green. The viewer can easily inspect the data visualizations for a 'simple rule' for determining if you can eat the wild mushroom

Stacked Bar Chart Multi-Plot - Cap Features

In [72]:
fig_size = (12, 6)
fig_title = 'Mushroom Cap Size Features - Poisonous vs. Edible'
cap_features_list = ['cap-shape', 'cap-surface', 'cap-color', 'bruises?']
row_counter = 0
column_counter = 0

# create plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=fig_size, dpi=dpi)

# iterate through multi-plot rows and colums
for feature in cap_features_list:
    ax_tmp = ax[row_counter, column_counter]
    feature_poisonous_tmp = df_mushroom_poisonous[feature]
    feature_edible_tmp = df_mushroom_edible[feature]
    
    # aggregate the feature value counts
    feature_poisonous_counts_tmp = feature_poisonous_tmp.value_counts()
    feature_edible_counts_tmp = feature_edible_tmp.value_counts()
    
    # create a dataframe to organize the value counts
    feature_df_tmp = pd.concat([feature_poisonous_counts_tmp, feature_edible_counts_tmp], axis=1)
    feature_df_tmp.fillna(0, inplace=True)
    feature_df_tmp.columns = ['poisonous', 'edible']
    feature_df_tmp['total'] = feature_df_tmp['poisonous'] + feature_df_tmp['edible']
    feature_df_tmp.sort_values(['total'], inplace=True)
    feature_labels_tmp = list(feature_df_tmp.index)
    
    # plot horizontal bars
    ax_tmp.barh(feature_labels_tmp, feature_df_tmp['total'], color='mediumseagreen')
    ax_tmp.barh(feature_labels_tmp, feature_df_tmp['poisonous'], color='indianred')
    
    ax_tmp.set_title(feature, fontsize=14)
    
    # switch to next plot
    if column_counter == 1:
        column_counter = 0
        row_counter += 1
    else:
        column_counter += 1

# set figure title
fig.suptitle(fig_title, fontsize=24)
plt.tight_layout()

Visual Correlation Analysis

After analyzing the feature values counts, I want to analyze the relationships between the variables. The correlations between the target variable and the input variables will be important for understanding which variables have useful information about the target variable, which we can use in our classification tasks. Additionally, the viewer can see correlations between the input variables to see if there are any macro patterns to investigate further

Create Correlation Heatmap

In [77]:
fig_size = (12, 12)
title = 'Mushroom Features Correlations'

# create a numeric dataframe with binary variables
target = (df_mushroom_long['class'] == 'edible').astype(int)
df_mushroom_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_mushroom_long.iloc[:,1:])
df_mushroom_dummies = pd.concat([target, df_mushroom_dummies], axis=1)

# drop feature 'veil-type' as it one has one category - 'partial'
df_mushroom_dummies.drop(['veil-type_partial'], axis=1, inplace=True)

# set up ticks and tick labels
dummy_feature_tick_labels = list(df_mushroom_dummies.columns)
dummy_feature_ticks = [d + .5 for d in range(len(dummy_feature_tick_labels))]

# get correlations
df_mushroom_correlation = df_mushroom_dummies.corr(method='pearson', min_periods=1)

# create a mask for upper right of triangle
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(df_mushroom_correlation, dtype=bool))

# create heatmap
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=fig_size, dpi=dpi)

sns.heatmap(data=df_mushroom_correlation,
            cmap='PiYG',
            cbar=False,
            square=True,
            mask=mask,
            ax=ax)

ax.set_xticks(dummy_feature_ticks)
ax.set_yticks(dummy_feature_ticks)
ax.set_xticklabels(dummy_feature_tick_labels, fontsize=5)
ax.set_yticklabels(dummy_feature_tick_labels, fontsize=5)
ax.set_title(title, fontsize=24)

plt.tight_layout()

This data visualization is useful for macro level analysis, but there are too many features (too hard to read) to focus in on the high correlation features and analyze them. What I decided to do next was to drop the features that had no significant correlation to any other variable. This dimension reduction strategy will help me to review the correlations of the importance variable to the target variable

Create Correlation Heatmap with Dimension Reduction

In [78]:
fig_size = (8, 6)
title = 'Mushroom Features Correlations (Reduced Set)'

# filter correlation data to only features with high correlations to target
threshold = .25

df_mushroom_correlation_high = df_mushroom_correlation['class'] > threshold
df_mushroom_correlation_low = df_mushroom_correlation['class'] < threshold * -1
df_mushroom_correlation_combined = (df_mushroom_correlation_high + df_mushroom_correlation_low).reset_index()
df_mushroom_dummies_reduced = df_mushroom_correlation_combined[df_mushroom_correlation_combined['class'] == True]
df_mushroom_dummies_reduced_list = df_mushroom_dummies_reduced['index'].to_list()
df_mushroom_reduced = df_mushroom_dummies[df_mushroom_dummies_reduced_list]

# get correlation matrix for the reduced feature set
df_mushroom_correlation_reduced = df_mushroom_reduced.corr(method='pearson', min_periods=1)

# set up ticks and tick labels
dummy_feature_tick_labels = list(df_mushroom_correlation_reduced.columns)
dummy_feature_ticks = [d + .5 for d in range(len(dummy_feature_tick_labels))]

# create a mask for upper right of triangle
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(df_mushroom_correlation_reduced, dtype=bool))

# create heatmap
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=fig_size, dpi=dpi)

sns.heatmap(data=df_mushroom_correlation_reduced,
            vmin=-1,
            vmax=1,
            cmap='PiYG',
            cbar_kws={"ticks": [-1, 0, 1]},
            square=True,
            mask=mask,
            ax=ax)

ax.set_xticks(dummy_feature_ticks)
ax.set_yticks(dummy_feature_ticks)
ax.set_xticklabels(dummy_feature_tick_labels, fontsize=6, rotation=45, ha='right')
ax.set_yticklabels(dummy_feature_tick_labels, fontsize=6)
ax.set_title(title, fontsize=14)

plt.tight_layout()

This heatmap is much easier to read and I can make comparisons better. Only the far left column 'class' really matters - as we want to see what variables have high correlation with poisonous/edible. I can see that odor_none is highly correlated with edible and that many variables are negatively correlated with edible - and that means that they are poisonous. The rest of the columns are interesting, but they don't get us any critical information

Using Machine Learning for Exploratory Data Analysis

At this point, I have finished the EDA portion of this tutorial and I have enough information about the features to start working on prediction/classification. My methodology is to fit the most accurate model that I can on the dataset, validate that model, and extract the feature importances from the optimal model in order to prove or disprove the null hypothesis

I am tuning the random forest hyperparameters 'depth' and 'features' in order to find the optimal model

Train Random Forest Model

In [79]:
n_trees = 1000
rf_max_depth_list = [d for d in range(1,11)]
rf_max_features_list = [f for f in range(1,101,10)]

# define processed X and y
X = df_mushroom_dummies.iloc[:,1:]
y = df_mushroom_dummies.iloc[:,0]

# split data into train / test partitions
test_split = .25
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=test_split, random_state=75, stratify=y)

# Create dataframe to store results
results_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=results_df_columns)

# random forest classifier grid search
for depth in rf_max_depth_list:
    for features in rf_max_features_list:
        
        model_name = f'RF_trees{n_trees}_features{features}_depth{depth}'
        
        print(model_name)
        
        clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=n_trees,
                                     max_depth=depth,
                                     max_features=features,
                                     bootstrap=False)
        
        # train model
        train_test = 'Train'
        
        clf.fit(X_train, y_train.values)
        rf_train_predict = clf.predict(X_train)
        
        # get confusion matrix and metrics for train partition
        confusion_matrix_train = metrics.confusion_matrix(rf_train_predict, y_train)
        
        total_records = len(X_train)
        samples = total_records
        
        true_positive = confusion_matrix_train[0,0]
        true_negative = confusion_matrix_train[1,1]
        false_positive = confusion_matrix_train[0,1]
        false_negative = confusion_matrix_train[1,0]
        
        true_positive_rate = np.round(true_positive / (true_positive + false_positive), decimals)
        true_negative_rate = np.round(true_negative / (true_negative + false_negative), decimals)
        false_positive_rate = np.round(false_positive / (true_positive + false_positive), decimals)
        false_negative_rate = np.round(false_negative / (true_negative + false_negative), decimals)
        
        accuracy = np.round((true_positive + true_negative) / total_records, decimals)
        precision = np.round(true_positive / (true_positive + false_positive), decimals)
        recall = np.round(true_positive / (true_positive + false_negative), decimals)
        F1_score = np.round(2 / ((1 / precision) + (1 / recall)), decimals)
        
        ROC_area = np.round(metrics.roc_auc_score(y_train, rf_train_predict), decimals)
        
        # save model training metrics
        results_df_tmp = pd.DataFrame([[model_name,
                                        train_test,
                                        test_split,
                                        total_records,
                                        n_trees,
                                        features,
                                        depth,
                                        true_positive,
                                        true_negative,
                                        false_positive,
                                        false_negative,
                                        true_positive_rate,
                                        true_negative_rate,
                                        false_positive_rate,
                                        false_negative_rate,
                                        accuracy,
                                        precision,
                                        recall,
                                        F1_score,
                                        ROC_area]], columns=results_df_columns)
        
        results_df = pd.concat([results_df, results_df_tmp], axis=0)

        # test model
        train_test = 'Test'
        
        rf_test_predict = clf.predict(X_test)
        
        # get confusion matrix and metrics for test partition
        confusion_matrix_train = metrics.confusion_matrix(rf_test_predict, y_test)
        
        total_records = len(X_test)
        samples = total_records
        
        true_positive = confusion_matrix_train[0,0]
        true_negative = confusion_matrix_train[1,1]
        false_positive = confusion_matrix_train[0,1]
        false_negative = confusion_matrix_train[1,0]
        
        true_positive_rate = np.round(true_positive / (true_positive + false_positive), decimals)
        true_negative_rate = np.round(true_negative / (true_negative + false_negative), decimals)
        false_positive_rate = np.round(false_positive / (true_positive + false_positive), decimals)
        false_negative_rate = np.round(false_negative / (true_negative + false_negative), decimals)
        
        accuracy = np.round((true_positive + true_negative) / total_records, decimals)
        precision = np.round(true_positive / (true_positive + false_positive), decimals)
        recall = np.round(true_positive / (true_positive + false_negative), decimals)
        F1_score = np.round(2 / ((1 / precision) + (1 / recall)), decimals)
        
        ROC_area = np.round(metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, rf_test_predict), decimals)

        # save model test results
        results_df_tmp = pd.DataFrame([[model_name,
                                        train_test,
                                        test_split,
                                        total_records,
                                        n_trees,
                                        features,
                                        depth,
                                        true_positive,
                                        true_negative,
                                        false_positive,
                                        false_negative,
                                        true_positive_rate,
                                        true_negative_rate,
                                        false_positive_rate,
                                        false_negative_rate,
                                        accuracy,
                                        precision,
                                        recall,
                                        F1_score,
                                        ROC_area]], columns=results_df_columns)
        
        results_df = pd.concat([results_df, results_df_tmp], axis=0)

By using a custom sorting priority order, I have selected the optimal model to minimize the occurrence of false positives. I did this because the priority should be on making sure that the model does not predict a mushroom is safe when it is actually poisonous. The outcome for the mushroom eater in the worst in this false positive scenario. Based on this prioritization, the optimal model has a false positive rate of 0% - which is reassuring

Model Validation

I used a 25% holdout validation set in order to tune the hyperparameters of the Random Forest model. In order to perform a more thorough validation of the optimal model, I will perform a KFolds validation analysis to ensure that the model is stable across different regions of the dataset. I have chosen to do a K4Folds as four folds yields a 25% holdout sample for each and that matches the holdout from the initial validation of the model

Conduct K-Folds Validation of Optimal Model Hyperparameters

fig_train, ax_train = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,6))
ax_train.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], transform=ax_train.transAxes, color='grey', ls='--')
ax_train.set_title(f'ROC Curve -- Train -- KFolds{n_splits}')

# create ROC curve testing fig, ax
fig_test, ax_test = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,6))
ax_test.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], transform=ax_test.transAxes, color='grey', ls='--')
ax_test.set_title(f'ROC Curve -- Test -- KFolds{n_splits}')

# assign x, y
X = df_mushroom_dummies.iloc[:,1:]
y = df_mushroom_dummies.iloc[:,0]

# split by K-Folds
kf = KFold(n_splits=n_splits, random_state=375, shuffle=True)

kf_counter = 0

# conduct K-Folds validation
for train_index, test_index in kf.split(df_mushroom_dummies):
    
    # split dataset
    X_train = X.filter(train_index, axis=0)
    X_test = X.filter(test_index, axis=0)
    y_train = y.filter(train_index, axis=0)
    y_test = y.filter(test_index, axis=0)
    
    # train model
    train_test = 'Train'
    
    clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=n_trees,
                                 max_depth=depth,
                                 max_features=features,
                                 bootstrap=False)
    
    rf_model = clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    rf_train_predict = pd.DataFrame(clf.predict(X_train), index=X_train.index, columns=['predict'])
    
    # get train partition results
    confusion_matrix_train = metrics.confusion_matrix(rf_train_predict, y_train)
    
    total_records = len(X_train)
    
    true_positive = confusion_matrix_train[0,0]
    true_negative = confusion_matrix_train[1,1]
    false_positive = confusion_matrix_train[0,1]
    false_negative = confusion_matrix_train[1,0]
    
    true_positive_rate = np.round(true_positive / (true_positive + false_positive), decimals)
    true_negative_rate = np.round(true_negative / (true_negative + false_negative), decimals)
    false_positive_rate = np.round(false_positive / (true_positive + false_positive), decimals)
    false_negative_rate = np.round(false_negative / (true_negative + false_negative), decimals)
    
    accuracy = np.round((true_positive + true_negative) / total_records, decimals)
    precision = np.round(true_positive / (true_positive + false_positive), decimals)
    recall = np.round(true_positive / (true_positive + false_negative), decimals)
    F1_score = np.round(2 / ((1 / precision) + (1 / recall)), decimals)
    
    ROC_area = np.round(metrics.roc_auc_score(y_train, rf_train_predict), decimals)
    
    # plot training ROC curve
    metrics.plot_roc_curve(rf_model,
                           X_train,
                           y_train,
                           ax=ax_train)
    
    # save model training results
    results_kfolds_df_tmp = pd.DataFrame([[kf_counter,
                                           n_splits,
                                           optimal_model_name,
                                           train_test,
                                           test_split,
                                           total_records,
                                           n_trees,
                                           features,
                                           depth,
                                           true_positive,
                                           true_negative,
                                           false_positive,
                                           false_negative,
                                           true_positive_rate,
                                           true_negative_rate,
                                           false_positive_rate,
                                           false_negative_rate,
                                           accuracy,
                                           precision,
                                           recall,
                                           F1_score,
                                           ROC_area]], columns=results_kfolds_df_columns)
    
    results_kfolds_df = pd.concat([results_kfolds_df, results_kfolds_df_tmp], axis=0)
    
    # test model
    train_test = 'Test'
    
    rf_test_predict = pd.DataFrame(clf.predict(X_test), index=X_test.index, columns=['predict'])
    
    # get test partition results
    confusion_matrix_test = metrics.confusion_matrix(rf_test_predict, y_test)
    
    total_records = len(X_test)
    
    true_positive = confusion_matrix_test[0,0]
    true_negative = confusion_matrix_test[1,1]
    false_positive = confusion_matrix_test[0,1]
    false_negative = confusion_matrix_test[1,0]

    false_positive_rate = np.round(false_positive / (true_positive + false_positive), decimals)

Analyzing Feature Importances

One of the best aspects of analysis using Random Forest models is that the model provides feature importance values and std for each feature. It is simple to plot these RF model feature importances with their std error bars

Extract and Visualize Random Forest Model Feature Importances

In [84]:
features = list(df_mushroom_dummies.iloc[:,1:].columns)
feature_std = pd.Series(np.std([tree.feature_importances_ for tree in clf.estimators_], axis=0), index=features)
feature_importances = pd.Series(clf.feature_importances_, index=features)
feature_importances_scaled = feature_importances * feature_std
feature_importances_df = pd.concat([feature_importances, feature_std, feature_importances_scaled], axis=1)
feature_importances_df.columns = ['importance', 'std', 'scaled']
feature_importances_df = feature_importances_df[feature_importances_df['importance'] > 0]
feature_importances_df.sort_values(['importance'], inplace=True)

# create a bar plot of the feature importances
fig_size = (8, 8)
fig_title = 'RF Model Feature Importances - Edible Mushroom Prediction'
features_reduced = list(feature_importances_df.index)
y_ticks = [f for f in range(len(features_reduced))]

# create plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=fig_size, dpi=dpi)

ax.barh(y=y_ticks,
        width=feature_importances_df['importance'],
        xerr=feature_importances_df['scaled'],
        align='center')

ax.set_yticks(y_ticks)
ax.set_yticklabels(features_reduced)
ax.set_xlabel('Importance', fontsize=14)
fig.suptitle(fig_title, fontsize=16)

plt.tight_layout()

Conclusion

In this project, I used advanced data visualization techniques and basic machine learning in order to conduct Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and to disprove the null hypothesis. Through visual feature analysis it is clear that mushrooms with habitat as 'waste' do not have any poisonous varieties. Accordingly, a 'simple rule' could be made which states "If the mushrooms are growing in waste, then they are not poisonous - go ahead and dig in"

Therefore, the null hypothesis that no such rule exists is false

I have also visualized the feature importances of the Random Forest model so that the viewer can see that many features contribute to predicting whether a mushroom is edible, so the scenario where a mushroom novice attempts to use a 'simple rule' to determine whether a wild mushroom is safe to eat would be a very dangerous thing to do. The exception to this is the waste rule that I just described
